date_year":1835,"date_month":7,"date_day":27,"children_ids":["HD6481","HD6482"]}],"tags":["minister","missionary","cherokee_mission","westward_migration"],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM891"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"He buried a wife and child mid-journey","body":"In 1821 Samuel Newton, his wife Betsey, and their children set out from New York with the United Foreign Missionary Society to establish Harmony Mission among the Osage. On the journey Betsey died near Shawneetown, Illinois, days after their newborn died near Louisville — a double loss before the mission was even reached."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"He married two missionary widows in turn","body":"Widowed on the trail, Samuel married Mary Hunt McCarty at Harmony Mission in 1822, the widow of fellow missionary John Seeley. After Mary died in 1835 he married a third missionary widow, Sophia Palmer Joslyn, whose first husband had also died in the field."},{"number":3,"category":"migration","header":"The first Protestant to settle San Antonio","body":"After missions to the Osage and Cherokee, Samuel brought his family to San Antonio in 1848, when the town had scarcely a shingled roof among its adobe houses. Family record holds he was the first Protestant to settle there permanently; he opened a private school and helped found the city’s First Presbyterian Church."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Six generations of Samuels before him","body":"Rev. Samuel Newton was the sixth Samuel Newton in unbroken succession — Samuel son of Samuel son of Samuel, back six generations to the immigrant minister Roger Newton. He carried that Connecticut lineage from a Woodbridge parsonage to the Texas frontier."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X02122","link_text":"Ainsworth Blunt","display_label":"served the same Cherokee mission field in Indian Territory"}],"slug":"samuel-newton-1792"},"I01795":{"id":"I01795","classification":{"